pH_clean

Chelsey Wegener

11/3/2020

Cleaning up environmental pH data: Going to remove flagged data first and then hopefully I can use a 7 day rolling mean window to remove outliers. Using rolling mean to remove data points that are +/- 2 standard deviations away from mean.

rm(list=ls())

Make custom function

custom_stat_fun_2<-function(x, na.rm=TRUE){
  m<-mean(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  s<- sd(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  hi<-m+2*s
  lo<-m-2*s
  ret<-c(mean=m, stdev=s, hi.95=hi, lo.95=lo)
}

China Camp

Read in and plot raw data

cc<-read.csv("C:/Users/chels/Box Sync/Thesis/Data/Working data/Bouy data/china_camp_all.csv", header = TRUE, sep=",", fileEncoding="UTF-8-BOM", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

cc$date<-as.Date(cc$DateTimeStamp, format = c("%m/%d/%Y"))

cc_raw<-cc%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=date, y=pH, color=pH))+
  geom_point(alpha=0.5)+
  labs(title="pH data from China Camp All data",
       subtitle="01/01/2017 - 12/31/2019",
       caption= "data courtesy of NERR")
cc_raw
## Warning: Removed 835 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Remove flagged data

cc<-cc[- grep("-3", cc$F_pH),]

7 day window rolling mean

cc_week<-cc%>%
  tq_mutate(
    select= pH,
    mutate_fun= rollapply,
    width= 672,
    align= "right",
    by.column= FALSE,
    FUN= custom_stat_fun_2,
    na.rm= TRUE)
## Warning in zoo(y, order.by = index(x), ...): some methods for "zoo" objects do
## not work if the index entries in 'order.by' are not unique

Filter and graph. Top=all data, bottom = filtered

cc_clean_data<-filter(cc_week, pH <hi.95 & pH >lo.95)

write.csv(cc_clean_data, "C:/Users/chels/Box Sync/Thesis/Data/Working data/Bouy data/cc_ph_clean.csv")

cc_clean<- ggplot(data = cc_clean_data, mapping = aes(x = date, y = pH, color=pH)) + geom_point()+ ylim(6.5,9)+
  labs(title="pH data from China Camp Cleaned",
       subtitle="01/01/2017 - 12/31/2019",
       caption= "data courtesy of NERR")



ggarrange(cc_raw, cc_clean, ncol=1, nrow=2)
## Warning: Removed 835 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
